SIMPLE: mummy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mummy
<hw>Mum"my</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧m"m⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mummies</plw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧m"m⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[F. <ets>momie</ets>; cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>momia</ets>, It.
<ets>mummia</ets>; all fr. Per. <ets>m⟦umac⟧miy⟦amac⟧</ets>, fr.
<ets>m⟦umac⟧m</ets> wax.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dead body embalmed
and dried after the manner of the ancient Egyptians; also, a body
preserved, by any means, in a dry state, from the process of
putrefaction.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dried flesh of a mummy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir. J. Hill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gummy liquor that exudes from embalmed flesh when
heated; -- formerly supposed to have magical and medicinal
properties.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au> <au>Sir T.
Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A brown color obtained from bitumen. See <cref>Mummy
brown</cref> (below).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gardening)</fld> <def>A sort of wax used in
grafting, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>One whose affections and energies are
withered.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mummy brown</b></col>, <cd>a brown color, nearly
intermediate in tint between burnt umber and raw umber. A pigment of
this color is prepared from bitumen, etc., obtained from Egyptian
tombs.</cd> -- <col><b>Mummy wheat</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>wheat found in the ancient mummy cases of Egypt. No botanist now
believes that genuine mummy wheat has been made to germinate in modern
times.</cd> -- <col><b>To beat to a mummy</b></col>, <cd>to beat to a
senseless mass; to beat soundly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mummy
<hw>Mum"my</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mummied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mummying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To embalm; to mummify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mummychog</ent>⟦br⟧
